[{'comment_id': 1299162384, 'comment_body': 'Are you sure both of these postStartCommands are necessary?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 19, 9, 27, 13, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hturner', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1299162804, 'comment_body': "Can you take this section out for the moment (save the code in a separate script for possible inclusion in a later PR). The behaviour on first starting the dev container should be just to print the welcome message. Then users should work through the README to build R-devel for the first time, as in v1.0 of the container.

We might provide the commands to build R in a script for convenience. But I think this should be used by people that are already familiar with building R and I don't think this script should be interactive (i.e. controlled by questions and answers). Instead, the script would be there as a reference, that a user could run all at once by sourcing the script, or they could customise, e.g. with their own choice of configuration settings, before running. In any case, that workflow is a separate issue from what we addressing in this PR, so we shouldn't change too much at once.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 19, 9, 31, 30, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hturner', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1299163925, 'comment_body': 'You have given the wrong file name here. Also, we use the opportunity to drop the file extension:

```suggestion
mv /workspaces/r-dev-env/scripts/rterm.sh /home/vscode/.local/bin/rterm
```

When you load the workspace make sure the script is in `~/.local/bin`, e.g. via `ls /home/vscode/.local/bin`. If it is then you should be able to run the script without giving the full path, i.e. just as `rterm`.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 19, 9, 42, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'hturner', 'type': 'User'}]
